>Q. Write a first version function called `generate_dna()` that generates a user specified length `n` random DNA sequence 

>Q. Modify the output to return a FASTA like sequence rather than a vector output


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna <- function(n){
  seq = sample(c("A", "T", "G", "C"), n, T)
  return(paste(seq, collapse = ""))
  ## similar output as using cat(seq, sep = "")
}
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna(25)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "TATATCCCATAATAAGGGTGAACAT"
```


:::
:::


Adding the option to return as a FASTA format or a vectorized output 


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna <- function(n, fasta = T){
  seq = sample(c("A", "T", "G", "C"), n, T)

  if (fasta){
    return(paste(seq, collapse = ""))
  }

  else{
    return(seq)
  }
}
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna(25) #FASTA format
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "GGTCTGAACAGGAATATGACTGAGA"
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
generate_dna(25,F) #vector format
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
 [1] "C" "A" "C" "A" "G" "C" "C" "A" "C" "T" "C" "A" "T" "C" "G" "C" "C" "T" "A"
[20] "G" "T" "A" "T" "T" "T"
```


